T1  - Historical Patterns of Inequality and Productivity around Financial Crises
AU  - PAUL, PASCAL
Y1  - 2023/10/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.13020
T2  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JF  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JO  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
JA  - Journal of Money, Credit and Banking
SP  - 1641
EP  - 1665
VL  - 55
IS  - 7
KW  - financial crises
KW  - productivity
KW  - income inequality
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.13020
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract To understand the determinants of financial crises, previous research focused on developments closely related to financial markets. In contrast, this paper considers changes originating in the real economy as drivers of financial instability. To this end, I assemble a novel data set of long-run measures of income inequality, productivity, and other macrofinancial indicators for advanced economies. I find that rising top income inequality and low productivity growth are robust predictors of crises, and their slow-moving trend components largely explain these relations. Moreover, recessions that are preceded by such developments are deeper than recessions without such ex ante trends.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Revolving versus Convenience Use of Credit Cards: Evidence from U.S. Credit Bureau Data
